To restore the entire SouthAfrica database:

1) As root, copy the local pg_hba.conf to /var/lib/pgsql/9.1/data. 
   Comment all 'all postgres md5' lines and uncomment all 'all all trust' lines.
2) As root, run 'service postgresql-9.1 start'.
3) Change the PostgreSQL postgres password, and create the ***REMOVED*** role as superuser:
    psql -U postgres
    \i role.sql

4) Gunzip the database schema dump you wish to load.
5) As superuser ***REMOVED***, create the SouthAfrica database and schema 
   (using ***REMOVED*** to do this ensures that all ***REMOVED*** extension 
    objects are owned by ***REMOVED***):
    psql -U ***REMOVED*** postgres
    \o SouthAfrica_schema.sql.out
    \i SouthAfrica_schema.sql
    (*** Ignore the 3 geometry_columns duplicate rule creation errors.)

6) As root, edit /var/lib/pgsql/9.1/data/pg_hba.conf, and uncomment all 
   'all postgres md5' lines and comment all 'all all trust' lines.
7) As root, run 'service postgresql-9.1 restart'.

8) As superuser postgres, remove superuser privileges from ***REMOVED*** role:
    psql -U postgres
    \i role_normal.sql

9)  Gunzip the database data dump you wish to load.
10) Load the database data dump:
    psql -U ***REMOVED*** SouthAfrica
    \o SouthAfrica_data.sql.out
    \i SouthAfrica_data.sql
    (*** ignore error re duplicate key value in spatial_ref_sys)

To configure daily database backups:

1) Execute:
crontab /var/www/html/afmap/mturk/crontabSetup
